### BACKGROUND IMAGE ###
if you use directly an image, it could corupt your grub menu (it'll reboot instead of showing your menu).

DO USE THE CONVERT FUNCTION TO BE SURE THAT YOUR GRUB WILL STILL BOOT

source of the image: "http://www.tux-planet.fr/public/images/wallpapers/linux/ubuntu/ubuntu-rust 1600x1200.jpg"

for example:
sudo convert ~/Downloads/"ubuntu-rust 1600x1200.jpg" -resize 1920x1440! -sharpen 5.0x1.3 -quality 80 -brightness-contrast -50x-58 -gamma 1.1 -crop 1920x1080+0+180 /boot/grub/themes/Crunchy-simple/ubuntu/ubuntu-rust.jpg

The sudo is only to have the right to write a file in the /boot folder.

### FONTS ###
the font, in grub, can be loaded only in one size per file. You can make the pf2 file with that command:

sudo grub-mkfont -s 20 -o /boot/grub/themes/Crunchy-simple/Ubuntu_normal.pf2 /usr/share/fonts/truetype/ubuntu-font-family/Ubuntu-R.ttf -v
or
sudo grub-mkfont -s 32 -o /boot/grub/themes/Crunchy-simple/Ubuntu_title.pf2 /usr/share/fonts/truetype/ubuntu-font-family/Ubuntu-R.ttf -v

-s: size
-o: output
-v: verbose (necessary to know how to call the font in theme.txt)

you can add too
-b: bold

The errors messages doesn't bother the efficiency of the resulted pf2 files.
The font can be found here: http://font.ubuntu.com/

Source for more than 800 fonts : https://fonts.google.com/
